  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-6551"><p>Hey Rebecca!  Just a question: I&#8217;ve seen so many recipes call for salting cucumbers before cooking with them and wonder why&#8230;</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Elizabeth</span></span>
  				<span>on December 2, 2009</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-6552"><p>Hi Elizabeth&#8212;thanks for reading! Well, as I say in the post, salting can draw out bitterness if the cucumbers are bitter, but mainly it draws off some of the water if you salt them and weight them, so they can absorb more of the dressing and the finished dish or salad won&#8217;t be so watery. Just remember to blot off most of the salt before proceeding with the recipe.</p></div>
  			<div class="date byline">
  				
  				<span><span class="alias">Rebecca (Mom)</span></span>
  				<span>on December 2, 2009</span>
  			</div>
  		</div><div>
  			<div id="item-6553"><p>See, when I was in France they were saying it was because cucumbers were indigestible otherwise, which made me a little suspicious &#8212; people in the US eat fresh cucumbers all the time!  Thanks for the info.</p></div>
